<p>Peak solar production in Maryland typically occurs from May through August, when longer daylight hours and higher sun angles maximize energy generation. During these optimal months, a typical residential solar system can produce 130-150% of a home's electricity needs, with excess generation credited back to the utility grid through net metering programs. Even during winter months, Maryland's solar systems continue producing valuable electricity, typically generating 60-70% of their peak summer output due to the state's relatively mild winter weather and occasional clear, cold days that actually enhance solar panel efficiency.</p>

<p>The state's solar production is further enhanced by Maryland's geographic position, which avoids the extreme weather patterns that can affect solar generation in other regions. Unlike areas prone to frequent severe storms or extended cloudy periods, Maryland enjoys relatively stable weather patterns that support consistent solar energy production throughout the year, making it easier for homeowners to predict and rely on their solar savings.</p>

